ndya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lisle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland, Durham, and Yorkshire): variant of   Lyle   and a cognate of 2 below.","French: habitational name from L'Isle or Lisle, names of several places in various parts of France, named with Old French <i>isle</i> ‘island’ (from Latin <i>insula</i>). Compare   Delisle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyle","meanings":["Scottish and English (of Norman origin): topographic or habitational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>del isle</i> ‘from the island’ (from Latin <i>de insula</i>), denoting someone who lived on an island or who came from a place in France named Ile, Isle, or L'Isle. The surname may also in some cases be from Lille (Nord). Compare   Lisle   and   Iles  .","Scottish: variant of   Lyall  ."]},{"name":"Lile","meanings":["English and French: variant of   Lisle  .","Scottish: variant of   Lyall  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":29,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Lisle was born in 1186, in Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England, his father, Robert de Insula, was 32 and his mother, Beatrice de Cormeilles, was 36. He married Sarah de Aunus before 1213. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1223, in Nedging, Suffolk, England, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1186–1223":"1186–1223","1190–1213":"1190–1213","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1213–1262":"1213–1262","1155–1213":"1155–1213","1150–1220":"1150–1220","1190":"1190","before 1213":"enne 1213","1220":"1220","1186":"1186","1262":"1262","Bef 1213":"enne 1213","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1213":"1213","1223":"1223","1189":"1189","1155":"1155","about 1220":"umbes 1220","after 1213":"pärast 1213","Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Nedging, Suffolk, England":"Nedging, Suffolk, England","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, Engla